answer.step_by_step_thinking:
\boxed{C}
**Clinical Reasoning:**
Papillary thyroid carcinoma, even when small, typically warrants definitive surgical management. Since the lesion is diagnosed as papillary carcinoma (Bethesda VI), a total thyroidectomy is standard, and lymph node dissection may be indicated. Radioactive iodine ablation is commonly given *after* total thyroidectomy to eradicate residual or metastatic disease. Therefore, administering RAI before total thyroidectomy—when the entire thyroid is not yet removed—is inappropriate because the thyroid cannot take up iodine once it’s destroyed; thus, RAI would have no therapeutic role until after complete thyroid remnant excision.

